1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:18,000
What are the steps we go through when we want to get access to a computer system?

2
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:33,000
We often refer to these as the access system.

3
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:38,000
What are the steps we go through when we want to get access to a computer system?

4
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:41,000
We often refer to these as the access control services.

5
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:44,000
There's four major access control services.

6
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:50,000
Essentially the steps that we have to go through to get access to a system and use that system.

7
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:58,000
Think about this. When you walk up to a computer system and you jiggle a mouse, what's the first thing that you need to do to get access to that system?

8
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:03,000
Hopefully, jiggling the mouse did just entirely unlock the system and give you full access.

9
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:07,000
Hopefully, there's some sort of access control services in place.

10
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:10,000
What's the first thing that you need to do to get access to a system?

11
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:18,000
The first thing you need to do is identification. Identification is where you assert your identity to the system.

12
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:24,000
You somehow uniquely identify yourself with a username or maybe biometric data.

13
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:29,000
So that is identification. It's where I identify myself to a system.

14
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:36,000
And hopefully, just typing in my username or which doesn't give me full access to the system.

15
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:40,000
Because the next step is authentication.

16
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:44,000
This is where the system needs to verify my identity.

17
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:48,000
It has to somehow figure out am I actually who I say am.

18
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:52,000
So how can the system authenticate me? Verify my identity.

19
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:55,000
Well, there are three factors of authentication.

20
00:01:55,000 --> 00:01:58,000
There's authentication by knowledge, something you know.

21
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:02,000
There's authentication by ownership, something you have.

22
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:07,000
And there's authentication by characteristic, how you behave or your physiology.

23
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:10,000
So those are the three factors of authentication.

24
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:13,000
And we'll get into those in a lot more detail later on.

25
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:17,000
Okay, so step one, I assert my identity, identified myself.

26
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:20,000
Step two, I authenticated myself somehow.

27
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:24,000
What's the next step? It's authorization.

28
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:29,000
This is where the system determines exactly what my access is going to be.

29
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:33,000
This is where we apply those principles we've already talked about, like least privilege.

30
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:35,000
Need to know separation of duties.

31
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:40,000
You don't want to authorize someone to have access beyond anything that they need to do their job.

32
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:43,000
So that is the authorization step.

33
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:47,000
There's one final and in fact, most important step.

34
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:49,000
And that is accountability.

35
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:55,000
The whole reason that we do access control is to make users accountable for their actions on a system.

36
00:02:55,000 --> 00:02:58,000
Because this is so incredibly important, we in fact give this a special name.

37
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:01,000
We call it the principle of access control.

38
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:05,000
So the whole reason and listen very carefully here because there's often questions on this.

39
00:03:05,000 --> 00:03:10,000
The whole principle of access control is accountability.

40
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:12,000
How do you achieve accountability?

41
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:17,000
Well, you have to have uniquely identified someone properly authenticated them, properly authorize them,

42
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:25,000
and then log in monitor what they're doing on the system to then and only then make them accountable for their actions on the system.

43
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:28,000
That is the principle of access control.

44
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:31,000
Let's talk about how we identify ourselves.

45
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:34,000
Identification ideally needs to be unique.

46
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:37,000
You do not want to have shared user accounts.

47
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:42,000
It's a very bad idea for 50 people in the organization to have all share one admin account.

48
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:46,000
So ideally identification needs to be unique.

49
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:48,000
Tied to a particular individual.

50
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:52,000
And the way that we identify ourselves are examples like I've already given.

51
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:56,000
User ID, account number, badges, which is a name and a picture.

52
00:03:56,000 --> 00:03:59,000
We can even use biometrics for identification.

53
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:03,000
Some good practices around identification, like I said, unique,

54
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:06,000
should also not be descriptive of your job.

55
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:11,000
So for instance, if I was the network administrator, I'd probably call myself network administrator god.

56
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:16,000
And the problem with that is that if there's any attackers on our environment,

57
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:19,000
what account are they going to try and break and do first, do you think?

58
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:22,000
Probably the network administrator god account.

59
00:04:22,000 --> 00:04:24,000
The other problem is that people change roles.

60
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:28,000
And what would inevitably probably happen to me is I would get demoted.

61
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:30,000
And I would no longer be network administrator god.

62
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:33,000
Now it would be network administrator lackey.

63
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:37,000
And my username would no longer apply to the role that I was in.

64
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:42,000
So it's not good for the roles to be tied to a particular description of what they someone does.

65
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:45,000
And then the final piece is secure issuance.

66
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:49,000
You need some way of getting someone their credentials securely.

67
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:55,000
So you don't ever just want to write out someone's username and password on a sticky note and leave it on their monitor.

68
00:04:55,000 --> 00:04:57,000
I mean, we're security people.

69
00:04:57,000 --> 00:04:58,000
We know better than that.

70
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:00,000
You got to stick it on a sticky note on the bottom of their keyboard.

71
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:02,000
That's how we do secure issuance, right?

72
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:03,000
Of course not, right?

73
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:08,000
But you need a secure issuance process, some way of getting these credentials to someone securely.

74
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:12,000
And the next few videos we'll talk about how we do these factors of authentication in more detail,

75
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:16,000
authentication by knowledge, ownership and characteristic.

